I visited this place in a middle of Covid- 19 madness. My choice did not betrayed me. Very decent and unique Italian restaurant with reasonable price with a friendly stuff at the historic merchant district, by the river ,under the bridges, great selection of wine. ( for a beer lover. Can you add little more  selection?) What more can I say? I had meat appetizer for 2 meat appetizer and meat spaghetti(I forgot the name, It was delicious.) This district used be a Fulton fish market under Mafia control.But Mayor Guliani kicked them out, more than 20 years ago. Nowadays,  Those days are gone, It is restored beautifully after hurricane Sandy.

We were very disappointed with our experience at Barbalu. Two appetizers, a salad and a side dish weren't brought to our table. One of our meals contained dairy, when it was made very clear that the person was allergic to dairy and it then took 15 minutes for the dish to be re-made while the rest of the group ate their dinner and waited for this person to finish.  The food was alright and if the service had been good, I would've given it three stars for an average restaurant.. but given that the food was average, service terrible, and it was pretty expensive -- I'd say spend your hard-earned dollars at one of the thousands of other restaurants in NYC.

One of the best Italian restaurants on the growing list of Italian restaurants on and around Front Street. We come here often. We enjoyed the tagliatelle Bolognese the baby arugula salad with shaved Parmesan is excellent as well. The pasta with porcini mushrooms was a little bland for me. But I did enjoy the fresh spinach pasta it's prepared with. All of the ingredients here are incredibly fresh. I believe all the pastas are handmade as well. The service here is wonderful as well. We come here often necessary the staff is very then the staff is kind and accommodating. They have an excellent list of wines by the glass that I enjoy. They offer sauvignon blanc, gavi, chardonnay, and a Pinot grigio, that are all good and all for $11.

I made reservations for my girlfriend and I at 830pm. We were 5 minutes late because of traffic. The host snobbed me when we entered. After we waited ten minutes, a group of 3 came in and was seated immediately. I asked for a manager because we were waiting another ten minutes. The host said they didn't have any tables for 2, when there were probably 7 open tables for 2. They seated us in a bad location and the waiter continued to be short and rude with us, so we decided to leave. Horrible service. I wouldn't recommend this place to my enemies. Our favorite Italian restaurant in NYC. We have been coming to Barbalu for a few years now and the food is still as good as the first day. The staff also have been there for a long time, I recognize them all. They are always very attentive and professional. Their burrata is to die for, and all their pasta dishes are excellent. If you are looking for Italian food and no the traditional way, this is the place to go. Plus, it's very romantic, and quiet. Perfect for a marriage proposal.

This is hands down the best Italian food in lower Manhattan. The ambiance is lovely and the staff are sweet and hospitable. The experts will help you pair wines with your food and you will not be disappointed.The food is unbelievable for dinner and also for private events. I've had 2 events privately catered by Stefano and his staff and I have been more than pleased. I received numerous compliments from my guests about the taste and presentation of the food, both appetizers and main courses. This is such an incredible little jewel that revived itself after the hurricane, and the renovations make it a really intimate setting.

I love the vibe here - I come here all the time with my coworkers, and this restaurant has exceptional service. However, do not get the wheat pasta. I'm not sure if they undercooked it, but it was hard........I learned my lesson for the next time, and I got my pasta the regular way - it is totally worth the extra calories. I usually get the Spaghetti al Bolognese (I probably totally butchered the spelling). My team always shares the Mozzarella appetizer - Yes, I don't remember the name to this either. And of course, you must always top your meal off with a glass of wine!

Good decor and ambiance but the food was middling.  The basic pasta sauce was simple and not full-flavored.  I did appreciate the GF pasta options.  The highlight to the meal was the beet and pistachio salad and $6 HH wines!  I would go there again for drinks and happy hour.

A few weeks ago, I visited this restaurant for the first time with colleagues from work. What a nice surprise to find that happy hour went late and the deal was excellent. That day it was buy one glass of wine, get one free. I am not sure if that is a rotating deal. My colleagues have been back since then and the happy hour deal was $6 glasses of wine. Either way, though, a great place to meet friends and enjoy great wine and food! Ambiance is really hip and inviting! I love the back area that is really open!

The atmosphere and the food was pretty decent. A wonderful and charming restaurant in the Seaport. I ordered a bowl of potato soup and gnocchi. Both were delicious. I asked the waiter if the soup had any dairy and *the chef* walked out to explain that it contained butter but no cream. Wine, Appetizer and Main was approximately $33 pp. They're working on opening a larger space, but the smaller bar area is decorated modern but very cozy. A great place for a business lunch, date, or just to treat yourself.
